### Classes in Java

A class is a blueprint for creating objects. It defines fields (attributes) and methods (behaviors).

---

### Declaring a Class

```java
public class ClassName {
    // fields (attributes)
    // constructors
    // methods
}
```

---

### Class Components

| Component | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| Fields | Variables that hold data |
| Constructors | Initialize new objects |
| Methods | Define behaviors |
| Nested classes | Classes within classes |
| Blocks | Initialization blocks |

---

### Access Modifiers

| Modifier | Access Level |
|----------|-------------|
| `public` | Accessible from anywhere |
| `private` | Accessible only within the class |
| `protected` | Accessible within package and subclasses |
| default | Accessible within the same package |

---

### Example Class Structure

```java
public class Car {
    // Fields
    private String brand;
    private int year;

    // Constructor
    public Car(String brand, int year) {
        this.brand = brand;
        this.year = year;
    }

    // Method
    public void start() {
        System.out.println(brand + " is starting");
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** By convention, class names start with an uppercase letter. A single Java file can have only one public class, and the filename must match that class name.

